<b><u>Chapter 7: The Labour-Process and the Process of Producing Surplus-Value</u></b> <a href="https://www.marxists.org/archive/marx/works/1867-c1/ch07.htm" target="_blank">(Read here)</a>
 
This chapter 




<b><u>Noteworthy excerpts and important questions for the left:</u></b>
<p style="color:#FF8B03";>
  1. <i>"The wealth of those societies in which the capitalist mode of production prevails, presents itself as “an immense accumulation of commodities,”[1] its unit being a single commodity.A commodity is, in the first place, an object outside us, a thing that by its properties satisfies human wants of some sort or another. The nature of such wants, whether, for instance, they spring from the stomach or from fancy, makes no difference."</i>
</p> Assumptions in terminology: capitalism. Does it make no difference if the desire is that of an essential necessity compared to a fanciful want? "From each according to his ability, to each according to his <i>need</i>"?

